{
  "texts": [
    "The SEM photo in Fig. 12 reveals the influence of zeolite on the concrete microstructure.",
    "Nandhini and Karthikeyan [93] found that incorporating 10% pulverized eggshell powder (PES) into concrete leads to a denser microstructure by enhancing the formation of calcium silicate hydrate (C-S-H) gel, which is crucial for the material strength and durability.",
    "However, they also noted that exceeding a 10% replacement results in increased stiffness and larger voids, potentially compromising the microstructure's integrity.",
    "Jaber et al. [95] observed that treated eggshell powder (TESP) improved crystallinity and calcium carbonate (CaCO3) content, enhancing the bond between cement and sand particles while filling pores.",
    "This improvement in the matrix's density resulted in better mechanical properties and durability by reducing permeability and increasing cohesion."
  ]
}